issue_body:
When task url is for example like `http://localhost/?q=<script>alert(1)</script>`
you can see alert on `/tasks` page:

![screen shot 2016-12-12 at 18 47 31](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3396041/21105494/7a76a516-c09b-11e6-9470-f3d3544c58cf.png)

This happened because data was not properly escaped here:
https://github.com/mher/flower/blob/master/flower/static/js/flower.js#L800-L804

The fix for this issue I think will be like this:
```js
  }, {
    targets: 4,
    data: 'kwargs',
    visible: isColumnVisible('kwargs'),
    render: function (data) {
        var entityMap = {
            '&': '&amp;',
            '<': '&lt;',
            '>': '&gt;',
            '"': '&quot;',
            '\'': '&#39;',
            '/': '&#x2F;'
        };
        return data.replace(/[&<>"'\/]/g, function (s) {
            return entityMap[s];
        });
    }
}, {
```
Or like this:
```js
}, {
    targets: 4,
    data: 'kwargs',
    visible: isColumnVisible('kwargs'),
    render: $.fn.dataTable.render.text()
}, {
```
`$.fn.dataTable.render.text` appeared in DataTables 1.10.10 (see https://datatables.net/manual/security)

I've encountered an issue with the current version of pyang. On March 8th, a fix was made to  an issue I raised regarding the missing validation of this rule from RFC 6087:

   If submodules are used, then the document containing the main module
   MUST be updated so that the main module revision date is equal or
   more recent than the revision date of any submodule that is (directly
   or indirectly) included by the main module.

However, the fix does not distinguish between the main module and a submodule so it is applying this rule to both. The result is that if I update a submodule, any submodule that includes it (which does not have an updated revision) now throws an error stating this rule has been violated.

For clarification, suppose I have the situation below.

module my-main-module {
  . . .
  include my-submodule-a;
  include my-submodule-b;
  . . .
  revision 2016-09-27 {
  . . .
}

submodule my-submodule-a {
  . . .
  revision 2016-09-27 {
  . . .
}

submodule my-submodule-b {
  . . .
  include my-submodule-a;
  . . .
  revision 2016-09-18 {
  . . .
}

pyang will throw an error complaining that the revision date for my-submodule-b is older than my-submodule-a. From the referenced rule in RFC6087, this does not appear to be a valid error.

I have verified that the same text exists in RFC 6087bis as well.

