Hello Pybind11 developers,

I trying to extend Pybind11 bound class in Python (inject new method to the bound C++ classes in Python, functionality similar to: http://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_64_0/libs/python/doc/html/tutorial/tutorial/techniques.html#tutorial.techniques.extending_wrapped_objects_in_pyt) And so far it looks like there is no additional C++ flags/code needed to enable this. Obviously simple extension on Python side will work for object created in Python but for objects created in C++ Boost require some extra code. Could you please confirm that Pybind11 classes does not need any extra tweaks to make this happened? Please find minimal example below.

Thanks,

```C++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <iostream>

struct Value {
	int a, b;
};

Value create_value() { return Value(); }

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(example) {
    py::module m("example", "pybind11 example plugin");

	pybind11::class_<Value> cl(m, "Value");
	cl.def(pybind11::init<>());
	cl.def_readwrite("a", &Value::a);
	cl.def_readwrite("b", &Value::b);

	m.def("create_value", &create_value);

    return m.ptr();
}
```

```Python
from example import *

Value.__str__ = lambda s: "Value({}, {})".format(s.a, s.b)
Value.foo = lambda s: s.a+s.b

print( 'Value create in Python: {} {}'.format( Value(), Value().foo() ) )
print( 'Value create in C++: {} {}'.format( create_value(), create_value().foo() ) )
```

Hi!

Thanks for the amazing work with pybind11! It's an incredible package and, having used the already very good boost python, I really appreciate the things you improved from there.


## Issue description

I just ran into a behavior which I'm not sure is intended. When using the std::variant support, it's possible to receive complex types from python or c++ and convert them into/from variant types. From how I read the implementation, it is intended to also be able to receive wrapped complex types from Python.

Whereas the conversion from c++ to Python of, e.g., a wrapped std::vector, works flawlessly, I am not able to push a vector from Python to c++.

## Reproducible example code

I am using mapbox variant implementation [https://github.com/mapbox/variant](here), but as far as I understand this shouldn't matter. The registration code is set up as described in the documentation and the conversion from c++ to Python is working flawlessly.

```
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>
namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_MODULE(tm, m) {
    m.def("test", [](const std::variant<std::vector<float>, std::vector<int>> &in) {
        std::cout << "received" << std::endl;
      });
}
```

```
import tm
tm.test([1, 2, 3])  # Fails.
```

